	(text "* Fast-role Swap MOSFETS,\n  as required by this\n  functionality (and as per\n  datasheets/app notes).\n"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 120.65 134.62 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.762 0.762)
				(color 72 72 72 1)
			)
			(justify left)
		)
		(uuid "55108f9d-f53b-46b6-a5fd-9047812f8371")
	)
	(text "* I2C/SPI isolation.\n* This IC is short on pins\n  and peripherals, so I2C and\n  SPI/I2S lines are shared.\n* I2C can only be activated\n  when the pins used for SDA\n  and SCL are not being used\n  for SPI or I2S.\n* Only external peripherals\n  and the on-board RGB LED\n  use SPI/I2S, hence why\n  their enable/select pins\n  are used to enable the I2C\n  lines.\n"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 82.55 123.19 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.762 0.762)
				(color 72 72 72 1)
			)
			(justify left)
		)
		(uuid "69020e24-607f-48d1-ac36-1cb35cc3d768")
	)
	(text "[soc-control] Microcontroller and USB-C PD Interface"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 82.55 19.05 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 2.032 2.032)
				(thickness 0.4064)
				(bold yes)
				(color 72 72 72 1)
			)
		)
		(uuid "87387611-b632-40bb-a896-606bcf3cdabb")
	)
	(text "* I/O pull-ups\n"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 82.55 110.49 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.762 0.762)
				(color 72 72 72 1)
			)
			(justify left)
		)
		(uuid "a37e45cf-436a-4189-b8a2-d69f3607f7e3")
	)
	(text "* Two main buses are routed throughout the board:\n\n  - USER: The USER bus is focused on controlling the board itself (SoC/MCU),\n    e.g. setting up configuration, issuing commands, retrieving collected\n    data, etc. This can be a multi-master bus, when cofugired as I2C. Also,\n    as a rule, in this bus, the board (SoC/MCU) acts as a SLAVE, but depending\n    on the mode of operation, this bus can be used as a secondary PHER bus.\n\n  - PHER: The Pheripheral bus is where the devices the board controls directly\n    are located; e.g. the fuel gauge, battery charger, miscellaneous devices\n    like screens or EEPROMs, etc. For this bus, the board (SoC/MCU) acts\n    strictly as a MASTER. Due to the way it's routed, the PHER can never safely\n    be a multi-master bus when configured as I2C.\n\n* The board operates in two distinct and fixed modes, programmable at the\n  firmware level:\n\n  - STANDALONE: The board is meant to run without supervision. It will be\n    configured by default in SoC/MCU firmware, or if enabled, interactively \n    via a pre-specified \"HAT\" (if supported; e.g. additional EEPROM storage,\n    screen with buttons, etc.). In this mode, the board acts as MASTER in\n    both USER and PHER buses.\n\n  - MANAGED: The board is meant to be controlled by a host system. The board\n    acts as a MASTER in the PHER bus, and as a SLAVE in the USER bus.\n\n* Both buses support specific communication modes, selectable at firmware level:\n\n  - USER: I2C or UART.\n  - PHER: I2C, SPI or I2S.\n\n  See Pinouts on the table to the side.\n\n* A secondary bus is derived from the PHER bus, the PHER_I2C (PHER_SDA and PHER_SCL).\n  The lines in PHER_I2C bus are isolated by a level shifter, and enabled only\n  when ~{PHER_EN} is deasserted (i.e. at 3.3V). I2C devices meant to be connected\n  to the PHER bus MUST connect through PHER_I2C.\n\n* For the USER bus, Pull-ups are always present, and pull to VCC, which can be either\n  3.3V or 5V depending on physical board configuration. However, PHER is nominally a\n  3.3V bus, and therefore has pull-ups to 3.3V (e.g. I2C). To the SoC/MCU all lines\n  are 5V-tolerant, however, try to avoid presenting 5V on the PHER bus."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 163.83 50.8 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1 1)
				(color 72 72 72 1)
			)
			(justify left)
		)
		(uuid "b4cd6a7c-777d-4256-89de-385699db4e7a")
	)
